<styl>crline <m0>From Herald Wire Services<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   Atlanta rallied for three runs in the ninth and Javy Lopez doubled in the winning run in the 10th Tuesday night to give the Braves their fourth straight victory, 6-5 over the Colorado Rockies.<ep>
   Curtis Leskanic (2-1) retired the first two batters in the 10th before David Justice walked and Lopez hit a 3-2 pitch to deep center. Larry Walker leaped against the wall but missed the ball by inches, allowing Justice to come all the around to score.<ep>
   Brad Clontz (1-2) pitched a scoreless 10th.<ep>
   Atlanta's ninth-inning rally prevented Greg Maddux from losing consecutive starts for the first time in nearly two years and cost Rockies starter Mike Farmer his first major-league win.<ep>
   Farmer, called up from the minors April 29, allowed only two hits in seven innings but Colorado's bullpen denied him the win in his first major-league start.<ep>
   The Braves rallied for three runs in the ninth on two-out, run-scoring singles by Ryan Klesko, Dwight Smith and Marquis Grissom. Leskanic went to two strikes on three straight hitters, but Jeff Blauser walked, Smith dumped an 0-2 pitch to left for a single and Grissom dropped a hit in left-center to score Blauser with the tying run.<ql>
